Note:
Task #477 regression test: a bare `Display <Integer>` must print the digits,
including the single digit "0" for the value zero.

The codegen-emitted print_integer routine builds the decimal string backwards
into a stack buffer. The convert loop ends with %rsi one position BELOW the
first digit, so the shared .convert_done `incq %rsi` lands on that first
digit. The zero special-case originally wrote '0' but did NOT perform the
matching decrement, so the shared incq overshot onto the null terminator and
print_integer(0) emitted an empty string. The fix adds the decrement to the
zero path so both print_integer and print_integer_nonl handle 0 correctly.

This test has no in-process stdout capture; it is a golden-output test. The
expected stdout is exactly:

  0
  7
  8
  -5
  0
  DONE

If the #477 bug is present, the first and the fifth lines (the two zeros)
appear as blank lines instead of "0". Exit code is always 0; correctness is
verified by the golden-output diff.
:End Note

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Note: Bare integer literal zero - the core #477 case.
    Display 0
    Note: A non-zero literal still works.
    Display 7
    Note: An arithmetic result that evaluates to a positive integer.
    Display 5 plus 3
    Note: A negative value carries its sign.
    Display 0 minus 5
    Note: A zero held in a variable also stringifies to "0".
    Let z be 0
    Display z
    Display "DONE"
    Return 0
End Process
